 Horst, Fritz, Gerhard, Dieter, Manfred, Arno, Bernd.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Kraus  .","German: from Middle High German <i>krūse</i> ‘pitcher, jug’; a metonymic occupational name for a maker or seller of jugs."]},{"name":"Cruise","meanings":["English: variant of   Cruse  .","Americanized form of German and Danish   Kruse   or Dutch   Kroese  ."]},{"name":"Cruze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jeanpaul, Guille.","Variant or an altered form of   Cruse   or   Kruse   or   Crews   or   Croes   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Crews","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): variant of   Cruse  .","Americanized form of German and Danish   Kruse   or Dutch   Kroes  ."]},{"name":"Crose","meanings":["English: variant of   Cruse  .","Americanized form of an unidentified German or Dutch surname, probably   Kroos   or   Kroes  ."]},{"name":"Crouse","meanings":["English: variant of   Cruse   2.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Kraus  .","Americanized form of Dutch   Kroese  ."]},{"name":"Crewse","meanings":["English: variant of   Cruse  .","Americanized form of German and Danish   Kruse   or Dutch   Kroese  ."]},{"name":"Cruce","meanings":["English: variant of   Cruse  . This surname is very rare in Britain.","In some cases also Italian: from <i>cruce</i>, a variant of <i>croce</i> ‘cross’ (see   Croce  ). This surname is very rare in Italy."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":102,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Cruse was born about 1280, in South Molton, Devon, England, her father, Thomas de Multon, was 17 and her mother, Margarita~, was 8. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with John Cruwys."},"et":{"about 1280–":"umbes 